 # 2×3 Signage Skill
  ## Setup & Usage Guide — VM Team

  ---

  ## Part 1 — One-Time Setup

  **1. Make sure Claude Code is installed**
  Open your terminal and type `claude --version`. If you see a version number, you're good. If not, install Claude Code first.

  **2. Get the skill file from Omaira**
  You'll receive a file called `signage.md` — save it somewhere you can find it (Desktop is fine for now).

  **3. Place it in the Claude commands folder**
  Open Finder, then in the menu bar click **Go → Go to Folder** (or press `Shift + Cmd + G`).

  Type `~/.claude/commands/` and press Enter.

  Drag the `signage.md` file into this folder.

  > Folder doesn't exist? Go to `~/.claude/` first, create a new folder called `commands`, then drop the file in.

  **4. Make sure you have the Python script**
  You'll need `apply_languages_new.py` saved on your Mac. Ask Omaira for the file path if you're unsure where it lives on your
  machine.

  **5. Restart Claude Code**
  Close and reopen Claude Code — it picks up new skills on startup.

  ---

  ## Part 2 — Using the Skill

  **1. Type `/signage` in Claude Code**
  The skill will load and prompt you to fill in your variables.

  **2. Fill in the variables**

  | Variable | Description | Example |
  |---|---|---|
  | Fixture Count File | Full path to your WW fixture count Excel file | `/Users/you/Desktop/JUN26_Fixture.xlsx` |
  | WW Fixture Counts Tab | Exact name of the tab in the file | `WW Fixture Counts JUN26` |
  | Country / Store Override | Any rule changes for this run — leave blank if none | omit if no changes |
  | Output File Name | What to name the generated output file | `JUN26_Signage_Output` |
  | Primary Language Column | Manually add this column to your Fixture Count file before running | Add to Fixture Count file first
  |
  | Secondary Language Column | Manually add this column to your Fixture Count file before running | Add to Fixture Count file
  first |

  > **China Division Note:** Stores in China are automatically split into two divisions — Shanghai and Beijing. Make sure your GLS
  sheet includes the China division column so the lookup works correctly.

  **3. Hit Enter — Claude does the rest**
  Claude will run `apply_languages_new.py` with your inputs and generate the output file automatically.

